In polar form, this becomes

\[z_{1}z_{2}=r_{1}\exp\left[\,j\theta_{1}\right]r_{2}\,\exp\left[\,j\theta_{2} \right]=r_{1}\,r_{2}\,\exp\left[\,j(\theta_{1}+\theta_{2})\right]\] (A.12)

that is, the magnitude of the product of two complex numbers is the product of the magnitudes of the two numbers, and the angle of the product is the sum of the two angles.

#### Division

This operation is defined as the inverse operation of multiplication. The quotient \(z_{1}/z_{2}\) is obtained by multiplying both the numerator and denominator of the quotient by the conjugate of \(z_{2}\):

\[\frac{z_{1}}{z_{2}} =\frac{(x_{1}+jy_{1})}{(x_{2}+jy_{2})}\] \[=\frac{(x_{1}+jy_{1})\,(x_{2}-jy_{2})}{x_{2}^{2}+y_{2}^{2}}\] \[=\frac{x_{1}x_{2}+y_{1}y_{2}}{x_{2}^{2}+y_{2}^{2}}+j\,\frac{x_{2} y_{1}-x_{1}y_{2}}{x_{2}^{2}+y_{2}^{2}}\] (A.13)

Division is performed easily in polar form as follows:

\[\frac{z_{1}}{z_{2}} =\frac{r_{1}\exp\left[\,j\theta_{1}\right]}{r_{2}\exp\left[\,j \theta_{2}\right]}\] \[=\frac{r_{1}}{r_{2}}\exp\left[\,j(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})\right]\] (A.14)

that is, the magnitude of the quotient is the quotient of the magnitudes, and the angle of the quotient is the difference of the angle of the numerator and the angle of the denominator.

For any complex numbers \(z_{1}\), \(z_{2}\), and \(z_{3}\), we have the following:

* Commutative laws: \[\begin{cases}z_{1}+z_{2}&=z_{2}+z_{1}\\ z_{1}z_{2}&=z_{2}z_{1}\end{cases}\] (A.15)
* Associative laws: \[\begin{cases}(z_{1}+z_{2})+z_{3}&=z_{1}+(z_{2}+z_{3})\\ z_{1}\,(z_{2}+z_{3})&=z_{1}(z_{2}z_{3})\end{cases}\] (A.16)
* Distributive law: \[z_{1}\,(z_{2}+z_{3})=z_{1}z_{2}+z_{1}z_{3}\] (A.17)